AI Model Gateway

A FastAPI-based multi-model AI gateway that provides a unified API interface for interacting with multiple large language model providers with streaming support.

This project integrates multiple LLM providers including DeepSeek, Qwen, GLM, and Kimi (Moonshot AI), and allows users to explicitly select which model to use through a single backend service.

The system is designed with a modular provider architecture, where each model is encapsulated in its own adapter layer, making it easy to extend new models in the future.

It supports OpenAI-style Server-Sent Events (SSE) streaming responses for real-time output and uses environment variables (.env) for secure API key management.

The current version focuses on explicit model selection rather than automatic routing, but the architecture is designed to support future enhancements such as intelligent routing, fallback mechanisms, and OpenAI-compatible API interfaces.

Supported Models
DeepSeek
Qwen
GLM
Kimi (Moonshot AI)
Architecture

Client → FastAPI Gateway → Router Layer → Provider Adapters → External LLM APIs

Each provider is implemented as an independent module, allowing easy extension without modifying core logic.

Database Design (Important)

This project uses MySQL with SQLAlchemy ORM.

What is stored

The database is used for chat persistence, not for model inference.

It stores:

Session information (conversation list)
User messages
Assistant responses
Model outputs per session
Tables
session

Stores conversation sessions.

id
title
message

Stores chat history.

id
session_id
role (user / assistant)
model (glm / qwen / kimi / deepseek / user)
content
Local Development Setup
1. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt
2. Configure environment variables

Create a .env file in backend folder:

DEEPSEEK_API_KEY=your_key_here
QWEN_API_KEY=your_key_here
GLM_API_KEY=your_key_here
KIMI_API_KEY=your_key_here

MYSQL_HOST=localhost
MYSQL_PORT=3306
MYSQL_USER=root
MYSQL_PASSWORD=your_password
MYSQL_DATABASE=ai_hub
3. Start MySQL

Make sure MySQL is running and database exists:

CREATE DATABASE ai_hub;

👉 Tables will be auto-created by SQLAlchemy:

Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine)

So you do NOT need to manually create tables.

4. Run backend
uvicorn main:app --reload

or (if packaged):

uvicorn backend.main:app --reload
5. API Access

Swagger UI:

http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs

WebSocket:

ws://127.0.0.1:8000/ws/compare
How It Works
Request flow
Client sends message
Backend saves session + user message
Router dispatches to multiple models
Each model returns response
Backend streams results via WebSocket
Results saved into database
Environment Security

This project uses .env for sensitive keys.

Important:
.env is NOT pushed to GitHub
Use .env.example for sharing config template
Features
Multi-model parallel calling
WebSocket real-time streaming
Session-based chat history
MySQL persistence
Modular provider architecture
Extensible routing system
Future Improvements
Intelligent routing (auto model selection)
Fallback mechanism (model failure retry)
Token usage tracking
Rate limiting
OpenAI-compatible API
Redis cache optimization
Authentication system
Deployment Notes

When deploying:

Ensure .env is configured on server
MySQL is accessible remotely or via Docker
Open port 8000
Use uvicorn --host 0.0.0.0 for external access
